{"title_page": "Jeffrey Zeldman", "text_new": "{{short description|American entrepreneur and web designer}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Jeffrey Zeldman\n| image         = Jeffrey_Zeldman_onstage_at_An_Event_Apart.jpg\n| image_size    = \n| caption       = Jeffrey Zeldman at An Event Apart\n| birth_name    = Queens, New York, US\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1955|01|12}}\n| death_date    = <!-- {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| death_place   =\n| body_discovered = \n| death_cause   = \n| resting_place = \n| resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}} -->\n| nationality   = US\n| ethnicity     = \n| citizenship   = US\n| other_names   = Lewis Jeffrey Zeldman, L. Jeffrey Zeldman\n| known_for     = [[A List Apart]], [[Designing with Web Standards]], Happy Cog, [[Web Standards Project]], An Event Apart, A Book Apart\n| education     = MFA Fiction Writing [[University of Virginia]],<ref name=Essmaker /> BA English [[Indiana University]]\n| alma_mater    = \n| employer      = [http://studio.zeldman.com/ studio.zeldman]\n| occupation    = Founder/Executive Creative Director/Publisher\n| years_active  = \n| home_town     = New York City\n| salary        = \n| networth      = \n| height        = \n| weight        = \n| title         = \n| term          = \n| predecessor   = \n| successor     = \n| party         = \n| opponents     = \n| boards        = \n| religion      = \n| spouse        = \n| partner       = \n| children      = Ava\n| parents       = Maurice Zeldman and Phyllis Sylvia Zeldman\n| relations     = \n| callsign      = \n| signature     =\n}}\n'''Jeffrey Zeldman''' is an entrepreneur, [[web designer]], author, [[podcaster]] and speaker on [[web design]]. He is the co-founder of [[A List Apart|A List Apart Magazine]] and the [[Web Standards Project]]. He also founded the design studios Happy Cog and studio.zeldman, and co-founded the A Book Apart imprint and the design conference [[An Event Apart]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Author|url=http://alistapart.com/author/zeldman|publisher=A List Apart|accessdate=5 June 2015}}</ref> \n\n==Early Life==\nJeffrey Zeldman was born on January 12, 1955,{{citation needed|date=April 2019}} in [[Queens]], New York, to the robotics engineer Maurice Zeldman<ref>{{Cite book| publisher = Marcel Dekker| isbn = 978-0-8247-7123-2| last = Zeldman| first = Maurice I.| title = What Every Engineer Should Know about Robots| location = New York and Basel| date = 1984| pages = xvii\u2013viii| url = https://archive.org/details/whateveryenginee0000zeld}}</ref> and his wife Phyllis Sylvia Zeldman.<ref>{{Cite news| issn = 0362-4331| title = Zeldman, Phyllis Sylvia (Gross)| work = The New York Times| location = New York| accessdate = 2019-04-14| date = 2000-10-30| url = https://www.nytimes.com/2000/10/30/classified/paid-notice-deaths-zeldman-phyllis-sylvia-gross.html}}</ref> When he was four years of age, his family moved to [[Long Island]]. When he was eight, they moved to [[Connecticut]], and at age thirteen, they moved to [[Pittsburgh]].<ref name=Essmaker /> He earned an undergraduate degree from [[University of Indiana]], and an [[Master of Fine Arts|MFA]] in fiction writing from [[University of Virginia]].<ref name=Essmaker />\n\n==Career==\nJeffrey Zeldman briefly worked as a reporter for ''[[The Washington Post]]'' and ten years as an advertising copywriter before turning to web design in 1995.<ref name=scanlon>{{Cite news| last = Scanlon| first = Jessie| title = Jeffrey Zeldman: King of Web Standards| work = Business Week| accessdate = 2019-04-13| date = 2007-08-06| url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070826093631/http://www.businessweek.com/innovate/content/aug2007/id2007086_670396.htm}}</ref><ref name=\"Essmaker\">{{Cite interview| interviewer = Ryan Essmaker and Tina Essmaker| last = Zeldman| first = Jeffrey| work = The Great Discontent| title = Jeffrey Zeldman: Designer, Entrepreneur, Writer| accessdate = 2019-04-14| date = 2012-08-28| url = http://thegreatdiscontent.com/interview/jeffrey-zeldman}}</ref> He rose to prominence as an authority on web design in the second half of the nineties by advocating a middle ground between the aesthetically oriented position of [[David Siegel (entrepreneur)| David Siegel]] and the functionally oriented position of [[Jakob Nielsen (usability consultant)|Jakob Nielsen]],{{sfn|Engholm|p=198}} viewing function and aesthetics as complementary rather than polar opposites.{{sfn|Engholm|p=200}} In 1998, he co-founded the [[Web Standards Project]] with George Olsen and [[Glenn Davis (web_design)|Glenn Davis]],<ref>{{Cite news| issn = 00104841| volume = 32| issue = 33| pages = 76| last = Sliwa| first = Carol| title = Browser standards targeted| work = Computer World| date = 1998-08-17}}</ref> serving as project leader from 1999 to 2002.<ref>{{Cite news| last = Holzschlag| first = Molly| title = The Web Standards Project Welcomes New Members, Defines Initiatives for 2003| work = The Web Standards Project| accessdate = 2019-04-13| date = 2003-02-14| url = https://www.webstandards.org/press/releases/2003-02-14/}}</ref> His persistent activism for the adoption of [[web standards]] has since earned him accolades such as \"standards champion,\"<ref name=\"dotnetmag\" /> \"godfather of web standards,\"{{sfn|Cederholm|p=236}} and \"a foremost advocate for the potential of the web.\"{{sfn|Apfelbaum and Cezzar|p=164}}\n\n== Web publications ==\nZeldman has maintained his personal website, Zeldman.com, since 1995, initially featuring a blend of web design tips, opinion, and entertainment. In the early years, the site included a humorous treatise on [[Lawrence Welk]],<ref>{{Cite news| page = R12| last = Sandberg| first = Jared| title = Hollywired \u2013 Star Track: In a Wired World, Celebrity Worship May Never Be the Same| work = Wall Street Journal| location = New York| date = 1996-03-28}}</ref> free icons and backgrounds for visitors to use, and a web design tutorial titled \"Ask Dr. Web\".<ref>{{Cite news| last = Williams| first = Martyn| title = Internet Update| work = Newsbytes| date = 1997-07-29}}</ref>  The site's Daily Report subsequently became \"a fountain of information regarding standards-compliant design.\"{{sfn|Cederholm|p=236}}\n\nIn 1998, Zeldman co-launched ''[[A List Apart]]'', a web magazine which explores the design, development, and meaning of web content, with a focus on the techniques and benefits of designing with web standards.{{sfn|Cederholm|p=234}} Among his many contributions to ''A List Apart'', his article \"To Hell with Bad Browsers,\"<ref>{{Cite news| issue = 99| last = Zeldman| first = Jeffrey| title = To Hell with Bad Browsers| work = A List Apart| accessdate = 2019-04-13| date = 2001-02-16| url = https://alistapart.com/article/tohell/}}</ref> published in February 2001, has been cited as a turning point in the adoption of [[Cascading Style Sheets]] for their intended purpose of articulating layouts.<ref name=scanlon /> \n\nZeldman also co-hosts ''The Big Web Show'', a podcast about the web and online publishing.<ref name=dotnetmag>{{Cite news| title = .Net Magazine Awards 2010: The Results Are in| work = .Net Magazine| accessdate = 2019-04-16| date = 2010-12-19| url = https://web.archive.org/web/20101222073254/http://www.thenetawards.com/}}</ref>\n\n== Design agency ==\nIn 1999, Zeldman founded Happy Cog,<ref name=Essmaker /> a web and interaction design studio specializing in user-and content-focused, standards-compliant design. In 2016, Zeldman's business association with Happy Cog ended, and he launched an independent design consultancy called [http://studio.zeldman.com/ Studio Zeldman].\n\n== Print publications ==\nZeldman has authored two books, ''Taking your Talent to the Web'', which was published in 2001,<ref>{{Cite book| publisher = New Riders| isbn = 978-0-7357-1073-3| last = Zeldman| first = Jeffrey| title = Taking your Talent to the Web: A Guide for the Transitioning Designer| location = Indianapolis| date = 2001| url-access = registration| url = https://archive.org/details/takingyourtalent0000zeld}}</ref> and ''[[Designing with Web Standards]]'', which first came out in 2003,<ref>{{Cite book| edition = 1st| publisher = New Riders| isbn = 978-0-7357-1201-0| last = Zeldman| first = Jeffrey| title = Designing with Web Standards| location = Indianapolis| date = 2003| url = https://archive.org/details/designingwithweb00zeld}}</ref> and appeared in two revised editions, one in 2007,<ref>{{Cite book| edition = 2nd| publisher = New Riders| isbn = 978-0-321-38555-0| last = Zeldman| first = Jeffrey| title = Designing with Web Standards| location = Berkeley| date = 2007| url-access = registration| url = https://archive.org/details/designingwithweb0000zeld_0}}</ref> and one in 2009.<ref>{{Cite book| edition = 3rd| publisher = New Riders| isbn = 978-0-321-61695-1| last1 = Zeldman| first1 = Jeffrey| last2 = Marcotte| first2 = Ethan| title = Designing with Web Standards| location = Berkeley| date = 2009}}</ref> ''Designing with Web Standards'' reiterates many of the arguments made by the Web Standards Project to highlight the benefits of standards-compliant web design.{{sfn|Kennedy|p=92}} Having been translated into thirteen languages, the book  brought standards awareness to a new international audience. \n\nIn 2010, Zeldman expanded his publishing work beyond web magazines with the creation of the A Book Apart imprint. Its books are designed to be quick reads and treat advanced topics in web design with a strong point of view.\n\n== Web Design Conference ==\nIn 2005, Zeldman and [[Eric A. Meyer]] founded An Event Apart, \"the design conference for people who make websites.\" An Event Apart is an \"intensely educational two-day learning session for passionate practitioners of standards-based web design\" followed by an optional day-long workshop on such topics as mobile web design, advanced accessible web design, HTML5, and CSS3. The conference currently takes place in seven cities annually. Cities and speakers vary. Speakers, in addition to offering informative content, must have made major contributions to web design or development in order to qualify to speak at the event.\n\n== Innovations ==\nZeldman and Happy Cog were early advocates of standards-based web design and many of their current and former employees have greatly contributed to various initiatives on the web, including:\n* The development of \"real type on the web\" via CSS and services including [[Typekit]].\n* Popularizing such ideas as [[CSS layout]], [[responsive design]], and style switching. The latter was an early 2000 innovation which paved the way for later third-party innovations including [[CSS Zen Garden]] and a web site known as Readability.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.readability.com|title=Readability}}</ref>\n* The second revised edition of ''Designing With Web Standards''', issued in 2007, which famously showed Zeldman with a blue knit hat on its book cover, inspired [[Douglas Vos]] to invent the [[Blue Beanie Day]]<ref>{{cite web | last=Walker | first=Alissa | title=Why Is Your Web Designer Wearing a Blue Hat Today? | website=[[Fast Company]] | date=2009-11-30 | url=https://www.fastcompany.com/1472960/why-your-web-designer-wearing-blue-hat-today | access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>, an annual international celebration of web standards which began in 2007<ref>{{cite web | title=Blue Beanie Day | website=Zeldman on Web & Interaction Design | last=Zeldman | first = Jeffrey |date=2007-11-19 | url=http://www.zeldman.com/2007/11/19/blue-beanie-day/ | access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n*{{Cite book| publisher = Rockport Publishers| isbn = 978-1-59253-895-9| last1 = Apfelbaum| first1 = Sue| last2 = Cezzar| first2 = Juliette| title = Designing the Editorial Experience: A Primer for Print, Web, and Mobile| location = Beverly, MA| date = 2014| ref={{sfnRef|Apfelbaum and Cezzar}}}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Cederholm|first1=Dan|title=Web standards solutions: the markup and style handbook|date=2004|publisher=Apress|location=Berkeley, Calif.|isbn=1590593812|edition=1st|ref={{sfnRef|Cederholm}}|url=https://archive.org/details/webstandardssolu00cede}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Clarke|first1=Andy|title=Hardboiled web design|date=2010|publisher=Five Simple Steps|location=Penarth [Wales]|isbn=1907828001}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Clarke |first1=Andy |last2=Holzschlag|first2=Molly E.|title=Transcending CSS: the fine art of web design|url=https://archive.org/details/transcendingcssf0000clar |url-access=registration |date=2007|publisher=New Riders|location=Berkeley, Calif.|isbn=0321410971}}\n*{{Cite journal| doi = 10.1076/digc.13.4.193.8672| issn = 1462-6268| volume = 13| issue = 4| pages = 193\u2013211| last = Engholm| first = Ida| title = Digital Style History: The Development of Graphic Design on the Internet| journal = Digital Creativity| date = 2002-12-01| ref={{sfnRef|Engholm}}}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Kennedy|first1=Helen|title=Net Work: Ethics and Values in Web Design|date=December 15, 2011|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|isbn=0230231373|ref={{sfnRef|Kennedy}}}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Keith|first1=Jeremy|title=Bulletproof Ajax|date=2007|publisher=New Riders|location=Berkeley, Calif.|isbn=0321472667|edition=[Online Ed.].|url=https://archive.org/details/bulletproofajax0000keit}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Shea|first1=Dave|last2=Holzschlag|first2=Molly E.|title=The Zen of CSS design: visual enlightenment for the web|date=2005|publisher=New Riders/Peachpit Press|location=Berkeley, CA|isbn=9780321303479|url=https://archive.org/details/zenofcssdesignvi00shea}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Stocks|first1=Elliot Jay|last2=Whitaker|first2=Keir|title=Insites: the book|date=2012|publisher=Viewport Industries|isbn=0957390505}}\n\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.zeldman.com/ Jeffrey Zeldman Presents]\n* [http://www.zeldman.com/about/#articles List of Select Publications]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zeldman, Jeffrey}}\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male bloggers]]\n[[Category:American bloggers]]\n[[Category:American designers]]\n[[Category:American men podcasters]]\n[[Category:American podcasters]]\n[[Category:American publishers (people)]]\n[[Category:American technology writers]]\n[[Category:American graphic designers]]\n[[Category:Internet pioneers]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from New York City]]\n[[Category:Web designers]]\n[[Category:Web developers]]\n[[Category:Indiana University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Virginia alumni]]\n[[Category:21st-century American non-fiction writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American entrepreneur and web designer}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Jeffrey Zeldman\n| image         = Jeffrey_Zeldman_onstage_at_An_Event_Apart.jpg\n| image_size    = \n| caption       = Jeffrey Zeldman at An Event Apart\n| birth_name    = Queens, New York, US\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1955|01|12}}\n| death_date    = <!-- {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| death_place   =\n| body_discovered = \n| death_cause   = \n| resting_place = \n| resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}} -->\n| nationality   = US\n| ethnicity     = \n| citizenship   = US\n| other_names   = Lewis Jeffrey Zeldman, L. Jeffrey Zeldman\n| known_for     = [[A List Apart]], [[Designing with Web Standards]], Happy Cog, [[Web Standards Project]], An Event Apart, A Book Apart\n| education     = MFA Fiction Writing [[University of Virginia]],<ref name=Essmaker /> BA English [[Indiana University]]\n| alma_mater    = \n| employer      = [http://studio.zeldman.com/ studio.zeldman]\n| occupation    = Founder/Executive Creative Director/Publisher\n| years_active  = \n| home_town     = New York City\n| salary        = \n| networth      = \n| height        = \n| weight        = \n| title         = \n| term          = \n| predecessor   = \n| successor     = \n| party         = \n| opponents     = \n| boards        = \n| religion      = \n| spouse        = \n| partner       = \n| children      = Ava\n| parents       = Maurice Zeldman and Phyllis Sylvia Zeldman\n| relations     = \n| callsign      = \n| signature     =\n}}\n'''Jeffrey Zeldman''' is an entrepreneur, [[web designer]], author, [[podcaster]] and speaker on [[web design]]. He is the co-founder of [[A List Apart|A List Apart Magazine]] and the [[Web Standards Project]]. He also founded the design studios Happy Cog and studio.zeldman, and co-founded the A Book Apart imprint and the design conference [[An Event Apart]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Author|url=http://alistapart.com/author/zeldman|publisher=A List Apart|accessdate=5 June 2015}}</ref> \n\n==Early Life==\nJeffrey Zeldman was born on January 12, 1955,{{citation needed|date=April 2019}} in [[Queens]], New York, to the robotics engineer Maurice Zeldman<ref>{{Cite book| publisher = Marcel Dekker| isbn = 978-0-8247-7123-2| last = Zeldman| first = Maurice I.| title = What Every Engineer Should Know about Robots| location = New York and Basel| date = 1984| pages = xvii\u2013viii| url = https://archive.org/details/whateveryenginee0000zeld}}</ref> and his wife Phyllis Sylvia Zeldman.<ref>{{Cite news| issn = 0362-4331| title = Zeldman, Phyllis Sylvia (Gross)| work = The New York Times| location = New York| accessdate = 2019-04-14| date = 2000-10-30| url = https://www.nytimes.com/2000/10/30/classified/paid-notice-deaths-zeldman-phyllis-sylvia-gross.html}}</ref> When he was four years of age, his family moved to [[Long Island]]. When he was eight, they moved to [[Connecticut]], and at age thirteen, they moved to [[Pittsburgh]].<ref name=Essmaker /> He earned an undergraduate degree from [[University of Indiana]], and an [[Master of Fine Arts|MFA]] in fiction writing from [[University of Virginia]].<ref name=Essmaker />\n\n==Career==\nJeffrey Zeldman briefly worked as a reporter for ''[[The Washington Post]]'' and ten years as an advertising copywriter before turning to web design in 1995.<ref name=scanlon>{{Cite news| last = Scanlon| first = Jessie| title = Jeffrey Zeldman: King of Web Standards| work = Business Week| accessdate = 2019-04-13| date = 2007-08-06| url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070826093631/http://www.businessweek.com/innovate/content/aug2007/id2007086_670396.htm}}</ref><ref name=\"Essmaker\">{{Cite interview| interviewer = Ryan Essmaker and Tina Essmaker| last = Zeldman| first = Jeffrey| work = The Great Discontent| title = Jeffrey Zeldman: Designer, Entrepreneur, Writer| accessdate = 2019-04-14| date = 2012-08-28| url = http://thegreatdiscontent.com/interview/jeffrey-zeldman}}</ref> He rose to prominence as an authority on web design in the second half of the nineties by advocating a middle ground between the aesthetically oriented position of [[David Siegel (entrepreneur)| David Siegel]] and the functionally oriented position of [[Jakob Nielsen (usability consultant)|Jakob Nielsen]],{{sfn|Engholm|p=198}} viewing function and aesthetics as complementary rather than polar opposites.{{sfn|Engholm|p=200}} In 1998, he co-founded the [[Web Standards Project]] with George Olsen and [[Glenn Davis (web_design)|Glenn Davis]],<ref>{{Cite news| issn = 00104841| volume = 32| issue = 33| pages = 76| last = Sliwa| first = Carol| title = Browser standards targeted| work = Computer World| date = 1998-08-17}}</ref> serving as project leader from 1999 to 2002.<ref>{{Cite news| last = Holzschlag| first = Molly| title = The Web Standards Project Welcomes New Members, Defines Initiatives for 2003| work = The Web Standards Project| accessdate = 2019-04-13| date = 2003-02-14| url = https://www.webstandards.org/press/releases/2003-02-14/}}</ref> His persistent activism for the adoption of [[web standards]] has since earned him accolades such as \"standards champion,\"<ref name=\"dotnetmag\" /> \"godfather of web standards,\"{{sfn|Cederholm|p=236}} and \"a foremost advocate for the potential of the web.\"{{sfn|Apfelbaum and Cezzar|p=164}}\n\n== Web publications ==\nZeldman has maintained his personal website, Zeldman.com, since 1995, initially featuring a blend of web design tips, opinion, and entertainment. In the early years, the site included a humorous treatise on [[Lawrence Welk]],<ref>{{Cite news| page = R12| last = Sandberg| first = Jared| title = Hollywired \u2013 Star Track: In a Wired World, Celebrity Worship May Never Be the Same| work = Wall Street Journal| location = New York| date = 1996-03-28}}</ref> free icons and backgrounds for visitors to use, and a web design tutorial titled \"Ask Dr. Web\".<ref>{{Cite news| last = Williams| first = Martyn| title = Internet Update| work = Newsbytes| date = 1997-07-29}}</ref>  The site's Daily Report subsequently became \"a fountain of information regarding standards-compliant design.\"{{sfn|Cederholm|p=236}}\n\nIn 1998, Zeldman co-launched ''[[A List Apart]]'', a web magazine which explores the design, development, and meaning of web content, with a focus on the techniques and benefits of designing with web standards.{{sfn|Cederholm|p=234}} Among his many contributions to ''A List Apart'', his article \"To Hell with Bad Browsers,\"<ref>{{Cite news| issue = 99| last = Zeldman| first = Jeffrey| title = To Hell with Bad Browsers| work = A List Apart| accessdate = 2019-04-13| date = 2001-02-16| url = https://alistapart.com/article/tohell/}}</ref> published in February 2001, has been cited as a turning point in the adoption of [[Cascading Style Sheets]] for their intended purpose of articulating layouts.<ref name=scanlon /> \n\nZeldman also co-hosts ''The Big Web Show'', a podcast about the web and online publishing.<ref name=dotnetmag>{{Cite news| title = .Net Magazine Awards 2010: The Results Are in| work = .Net Magazine| accessdate = 2019-04-16| date = 2010-12-19| url = https://web.archive.org/web/20101222073254/http://www.thenetawards.com/}}</ref>\n\n== Design agency ==\nIn 1999, Zeldman founded Happy Cog,<ref name=Essmaker /> a web and interaction design studio specializing in user-and content-focused, standards-compliant design. In 2016, Zeldman's business association with Happy Cog ended, and he launched an independent design consultancy called [http://studio.zeldman.com/ Studio Zeldman].\n\n== Print publications ==\nZeldman has authored two books, ''Taking your Talent to the Web'', which was published in 2001,<ref>{{Cite book| publisher = New Riders| isbn = 978-0-7357-1073-3| last = Zeldman| first = Jeffrey| title = Taking your Talent to the Web: A Guide for the Transitioning Designer| location = Indianapolis| date = 2001| url-access = registration| url = https://archive.org/details/takingyourtalent0000zeld}}</ref> and ''[[Designing with Web Standards]]'', which first came out in 2003,<ref>{{Cite book| edition = 1st| publisher = New Riders| isbn = 978-0-7357-1201-0| last = Zeldman| first = Jeffrey| title = Designing with Web Standards| location = Indianapolis| date = 2003| url = https://archive.org/details/designingwithweb00zeld}}</ref> and appeared in two revised editions, one in 2007,<ref>{{Cite book| edition = 2nd| publisher = New Riders| isbn = 978-0-321-38555-0| last = Zeldman| first = Jeffrey| title = Designing with Web Standards| location = Berkeley| date = 2007| url-access = registration| url = https://archive.org/details/designingwithweb0000zeld_0}}</ref> and one in 2009.<ref>{{Cite book| edition = 3rd| publisher = New Riders| isbn = 978-0-321-61695-1| last1 = Zeldman| first1 = Jeffrey| last2 = Marcotte| first2 = Ethan| title = Designing with Web Standards| location = Berkeley| date = 2009}}</ref> ''Designing with Web Standards'' reiterates many of the arguments made by the Web Standards Project to highlight the benefits of standards-compliant web design.{{sfn|Kennedy|p=92}} Having been translated into thirteen languages, the book  brought standards awareness to a new international audience. \n\nIn 2010, Zeldman expanded his publishing work beyond web magazines with the creation of the A Book Apart imprint. Its books are designed to be quick reads and treat advanced topics in web design with a strong point of view.\n\n== Web Design Conference ==\nIn 2005, Zeldman and [[Eric A. Meyer]] founded An Event Apart, \"the design conference for people who make websites.\" An Event Apart is an \"intensely educational two-day learning session for passionate practitioners of standards-based web design\" followed by an optional day-long workshop on such topics as mobile web design, advanced accessible web design, HTML5, and CSS3. The conference currently takes place in seven cities annually. Cities and speakers vary. Speakers, in addition to offering informative content, must have made major contributions to web design or development in order to qualify to speak at the event.\n\n== Innovations ==\nZeldman and Happy Cog were early advocates of standards-based web design and many of their current and former employees have greatly contributed to various initiatives on the web, including:\n* The development of \"real type on the web\" via CSS and services including [[Typekit]].\n* Popularizing such ideas as [[CSS layout]], [[responsive design]], and style switching. The latter was an early 2000 innovation which paved the way for later third-party innovations including [[CSS Zen Garden]] and a web site known as Readability.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.readability.com|title=Readability}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n*{{Cite book| publisher = Rockport Publishers| isbn = 978-1-59253-895-9| last1 = Apfelbaum| first1 = Sue| last2 = Cezzar| first2 = Juliette| title = Designing the Editorial Experience: A Primer for Print, Web, and Mobile| location = Beverly, MA| date = 2014| ref={{sfnRef|Apfelbaum and Cezzar}}}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Cederholm|first1=Dan|title=Web standards solutions: the markup and style handbook|date=2004|publisher=Apress|location=Berkeley, Calif.|isbn=1590593812|edition=1st|ref